column123: My exposure to the Effective Altruism movement has caused me to believe I have a strong moral obligation to save distant lives, but on noticing I felt little of no guilt about failing to live up to those obligations, have decided I'm amoral (or at least, my utility function rates morality as very low importance), and so consciously avoid altruism of the because-it's-right-not-because-warm-fuzzies type that Effective Altruism is all about.  Are there more people who reacted the way I did? Should this be taken into account when deciding to publicise EA, or am I just a mutant?

column123: I'm worried that the answers to these questions will be misinterpreted in various ways. E.g. I don't identify as a feminist not because I don't care about women but because I want to keep my identity small and because I have reservations about the epistemic health of the social justice community. It seems important to distinguish between 'I don't identify as X and don't agree with X's goals' and 'I don't identify as X but agree with X's goals.' column123:
I feel like there are categories missing from the types of charities you mention. Is that intentional? Why?

I'd like to put in a good word for Engineers Without Borders Canada (not the same as the United States organization.) I worked to build that organization for several years. I continue to be impressed by it. EWB has created an annual failure report, to get people discussing international development failures, and how to make things better. EWB also successfully advocated to the public, and lobbied the government, to 'untie' aid (that is, to stop making international assistance linked to deals for Canadian companies,) and the Canadian federal government did it.

I have learned so much about how the world works by being involved in that organization, and it is one of the few organizations that I've come across that seems to learn as an organization and is continually working to become better.

I'm not totally familiar with the term effective altruism as it is being applied here, but I do care about the effectiveness of charities and of actions taken to make the world a better place.

I have come to appreciate how complex these issues are, and how some of the consequences of interventions can be counter-intuitive.

I would caution against only giving to charities with metrics that appear good. There are some things that we haven't figured out a good way to measure, and metrics can be gamed.

In international development, I have observed that there is often a choice between doing a short term project that can be measured easily or taking a long term ongoing supporting role. They both have benefits and drawbacks, and the easily measured (and easier to sell to donors) approach is not always better.

I would also say that although I care about the welfare of animals, I do not want to be associated with groups such as PETA, who I think are counterproductive, and so I did not check the box for Animal Rights. I would like to see changes in how mainstream agriculture treats animals (and I buy only free-range meat) and I would like to see humans stop destroying habitat for all sorts of creatures (this is one reason why I donate to the Land Trust charity, though I wish our political and economic system was set up better so that this wasn't a problem in the first place.)

I do not feel like 'left' or 'right' can accurately describe my political beliefs, so I didn't answer that question. Probably, since I am Canadian, they look like 'left' to Americans, from a very oversimplified point of view.

This survey seems to be USA-centric. It would be nice to see a more international view represented.

column37: I'm not sure what it is to identify with a movement. I care about animals, the environment, feminism, LGBTQ issues, identifying and overcoming cognitive biases, overcoming the limitations of the human body, and questioning traditional world views. But I don't know if I would *identify* with any of these movements. Likewise, I'm not sure if I would *identify* as an EA. I can certainly be described as an EA, just as I could be described as an environmentalist, feminist, etc., but I would not *identify* with those movements. I'm somewhat attracted to libertarianism as a political view, but I would hesitate to *identify* myself as a libertarian. I'm generally averse to *identifying* myself as anything, although it's true that I hold views that are often in line with various social movements.

column100: I guess you could call me a hard-line altruist who believes that money should be spent on people willing to help themselves rather than merely doled out as a social benefit.   I respond better to cases when the situation isn't a) self-inflicted or b)solveable in some other way without resorting to an aid system.   For this reason I'll favor medical research for genetic diseases over say, social welfare for able-bodied people who just lack the motivation to work.    I believe the most effective use of donation money would be on treating the symptom not the cause and while this may not seem the most humanitarian of stances I believe this offers the best hope for improving the world.

column100: I feel I should justify the rather pitiful donations I have made thus far- In the two years that I have known about EA and GWWC I have been taking my BPhil in Philosophy at Oxford.  This has been self funded, and the total tuition/college costs works out to about $30,000 Canadian a year.  Since I am going into debt in order to fund my education, it seemed counter-intutive to make substantial donations as doing so will have lead to double-donating (presuming a donate 10% of my pre-debt-repayment income).  As such, I have only channeled about 5% of my total living expenses toward my charity of choice.  Once I start making a positive income in September, I plan to make a 10% donation of my pre-debt-repayment income every month.

column123: I am young and I have not done much with my life but I am not Idle I have taken many steps in advancing the life in the way I want and am close to taking another step in my plans by going to University of Oregon. I shall continue to donate when I can and I will hopefully reach my goal and be able to do more than just donate money to the orginizations and sciences I believe in.
